{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510400"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:28:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:28:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11544"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11544"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.66,0.23,0.05,0.05,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4173"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78798"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4173","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4173"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11544"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64147"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2770"},{"type":"tags","id":"3051"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"6219"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5397"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5428"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9658"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9820"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26987"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30369"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35809"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35973"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78798"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman visited her general practitioner with a two month history of troublesome joint pains in her wrists and hands. These joints exhibit stiffness, particularly in the early mornings, and this may last for more than an hour. She has a history of chronic alcohol use disorder and has been referred to the Drug and Alcohol Services for further management. She recalls having an allergic reaction to co-trimoxazole when taking it for a urinary tract infection a few years ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she has swollen and tender metacarpophalangeal and proximal interphalangeal joints bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer blood test results show the following:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHb: 101 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMCV: 92 fL (80-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWCC: 13.2 \u00d7 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4-11)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EESR: 48 mm/h (\u0026lt;12)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGGT: 188 U/L (5-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALT: 94 U/L (\u0026lt;51)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAST: 74 U/L (\u0026lt;36)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERheumatoid factor (RF): 109 IU/mL (\u0026lt;20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnti-cyclic citrullinated peptides antibodies (anti-CCP): 133 U/mL (\u0026lt;20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Methotrexate + folic acid","Hydroxychloroquine","Sulfasalazine","Infliximab","Tofacitinib"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid arthritis (RA) \u003C/strong\u003Eis the likely diagnosis for this patient who presents with symmetrical polyarthritis affecting the wrist and hand joints. The metacarpophalangeal and proximal interphalangeal joints of the fingers are commonly affected, but other large joints can be affected. The elevated inflammatory markers, RF, anti-CCP, and normocytic anaemia due to chronic inflammation are supportive of the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERA is most common in the third through fifth decades of life, and is 2-3 times more common in women than men (1). In addition, cigarette smoking is a strong risk factor for the disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDisease-modifying antirheumatic drugs (DMARDs) should be started as soon as possible after the diagnosis of RA to prevent progressive joint damage. The three classes of DMARDs and their examples are listed as below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Econventional: methotrexate, leflunomide, hydroxychloroquine, sulfasalazine\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ebiologics: tumour necrosis factor alpha (TNF-\u03b1) antagonist (e.g., infliximab), T-cell costimulation antagonist (e.g., abatacept), interleukin-6 receptor antagonist (e.g., tocilizumab), and anti-CD20 monoclonal antibody (e.g., rituximab)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Etargeted synthetic: JAK inhibitor (e.g., tofacitinib)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethotrexate \u003C/strong\u003Eis the recommended first-line DMARD for most patients. However, when selecting therapy, it is crucial to consider other factors such as pregnancy, lactation and comorbidities. Methotrexate should be avoided in patients with chronic liver disease and significant pulmonary disease due to its potential for liver and pulmonary toxicity. Additionally, patients with alcohol-use disorder should not be prescribed methotrexate because of the combined detrimental effects on the liver. Pregnant individuals should also avoid methotrexate and instead, hydroxychloroquine and sulfasalazine are preferred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients on chronic low-dose methotrexate treatment should be prescribed \u003Cstrong\u003Efolic acid\u003C/strong\u003E to reduce the risk of common methotrexate toxicities, such as gastrointestinal symptoms and hepatic transaminase elevations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn cases where methotrexate is contraindicated, alternative DMARDs should be considered. In this case, however, \u003Cstrong\u003Esulfasalazine \u003C/strong\u003Eis not preferred due to documented allergy to co-trimoxazole, also known as trimethoprim/sulfamethoxazole (TMP/SMX). These are sulfonamides hence there is a high risk of cross-allergenicity. \u003Cstrong\u003EHydroxychloroquine \u003C/strong\u003Eand leflunomide are therefore most suitable for this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn most cases, methotrexate is the backbone of disease-modifying therapy. If this is insufficient, other conventional DMARDs such as hydroxychloroquine and sulfasalazine are added. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ebiologic and targeted synthetic DMARDs\u003C/strong\u003E are options if the disease remains uncontrolled.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe DMARDs have different adverse effect profiles, but important ones to be aware of are infection, myelosuppression, hepatotoxicity, and increased risk of malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Disease-modifying antirheumatic drugs should be commenced as soon as possible after the diagnosis of rheumatoid arthritis.","Methotrexate is the recommended initial disease-modifying therapy for most patients with rheumatoid arthritis.","Methotrexate is contraindicated in severe liver disease, pregnancy, and lactation."],"references":["Gravallese EM, Firestein GS. Rheumatoid Arthritis - Common Origins, Divergent Mechanisms. N Engl J Med. 2023 Feb 9;388(6):529-542. doi: 10.1056/NEJMra2103726. PMID: 36780677. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36780677/","Fraenkel L, Bathon JM, England BR, St Clair EW, Arayssi T, Carandang K, Deane KD, Genovese M, Huston KK, Kerr G, Kremer J, Nakamura MC, Russell LA, Singh JA, Smith BJ, Sparks JA, Venkatachalam S, Weinblatt ME, Al-Gibbawi M, Baker JF, Barbour KE, Barton JL, Cappelli L, Chamseddine F, George M, Johnson SR, Kahale L, Karam BS, Khamis AM, Navarro-Mill\u00e1n I, Mirza R, Schwab P, Singh N, Turgunbaev M, Turner AS, Yaacoub S, Akl EA. 2021 American College of Rheumatology Guideline for the Treatment of Rheumatoid Arthritis. Arthritis Rheumatol. 2021 Jul;73(7):1108-1123. doi: 10.1002/art.41752. Epub 2021 Jun 8. PMID: 34101376. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34101376/","Wilsdon TD, Hill CL. Managing the drug treatment of rheumatoid arthritis. [cited 2022 Feb 11]; Available from: https://www.nps.org.au/australian-prescriber/articles/managing-the-drug-treatment-of-rheumatoid-arthritis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64147"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11544"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64147"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T18:53:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T18:54:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4173"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78798"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHead